%U A396316 53,39,11,14,19,29,59,6,61,31,12,126,13,11,67,17,23,7,71,14,73,37,30
%N A396316 Numerator of the largest abundancy of any proper divisor of n as a fraction of the abundancy of n.
%C A396316 The numerator is that of the reduced fraction. The abundancy of k is sigma(k)/k, where sigma is the sum of divisors function, A000203.
%C A396316 Note that for many integers, including all squarefree n, a(n) is the same as A006530(n), the greatest prime factor of n. The numbers for which they differ are listed in A396314.
%F A396316 For e > 0, a(prime(k)^e) = Sum_{j=1..e} prime(k)^j = A319076(e,k) - 1, where prime(k) = A000040(k) is the k-th prime.
%F A396316 For i, j > 1, a(lcm(i, j)) = max(a(i), a(j)).
%F A396316 a(n) = i/gcd(i, j), where i = sigma(A395192(n))*n, j = A395192(n)*sigma(n) and A395192(n) is the least proper divisor of n with the greatest abundancy.
%F A396316 a(n) = A396319(n) - 1.
%F A396316 a(n) = n iff n is prime.
%e A396316 For any number n, we need consider only its maximal proper divisors (row n of A355079), since the abundancy of any number is never greater than that of any of its multiples.
%e A396316 For n = 20, we consider 10 and 4. The abundancy of 10 is sigma(10)/10 = 18/10 = 1.8. The abundancy of 4 is sigma(4)/4 = 7/4 = 1.75. The larger of these is 1.8. As a fraction of the abundancy of 20, which is 42/20 = 2.1, this is 1.8/2.1 = 6/7, whose numerator is 6. So a(20) = 6.
%Y A396316 Cf. A017665/A017666 (abundancy), A355079, A396319 (denominators).
%Y A396316 See the comments for the relationships with A000203, A006530, A396314.
%Y A396316 See the formula section for the relationships with A000040, A319076, A395192.
%K A396316 nonn,frac,new
